<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="section-RMR">
    <title>Rectilinear Motion Revisited</title>
    <p>
        Recall that if <m>x(t)</m> represents the position of an object along a straight line, then its velocity is given by <m>v(t) = x'(t)</m>, and its acceleration is given by <m>a(t) = v'(t) = x''(t)</m>.
    </p>

    <ul>
        <li>If <m>v(t) > 0</m>, then the particle is <term>moving to the right</term>. If <m>v(t) \lt 0</m>, then the particle is moving to the left.</li>
        <li>The particle is <term>at rest</term> if <m>v(t) = 0</m>.</li>
        <li>The particle <term>changes direction</term> if <m>v(t)</m> changes sign (either from positive to negative, or vise versa).</li>
        <li>If <m>a(t) > 0</m>, then the particle is accelerating to the right. If <m>a(t) \lt 0</m>, then the particle is accelerating to the left.</li>
        <li>If <m>v(t)</m> and <m>a(t)</m> have the same sign, then the particle is <term>speeding up</term>. If <m>v(t)</m> and <m>a(t)</m> have opposite signs, then the particle is <term>slowing down</term>.</li>
    </ul>
</section>